 Cumbria near Carlisle, named from Old Norse <i>kirkja</i> ‘church’ + the Irish saint's name <i>Bride</i> (see   Kilbride  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Kilbride","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Kieran, Aidan.","Irish (Connacht) and Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Brighde</b> (Irish) or <b>Mac Gille Brighde</b> (Scottish) ‘son of the servant of (Saint) Brigit’, also often shortened and Anglicized as   McBride  . The name <i>Brigit</i> means ‘exalted’. Brigit was originally a pagan goddess, many of whose attributes, such as a sacred fire, became attached to the historical figure of Saint Brigit of Kildare (452–523), founder of the first Irish convent.","Scottish: habitational name from any of various places with this name, from Gaelic <i>Cill Bríghde</i> ‘church of Saint Brigit’ (<i>cill</i> being from Latin <i>cella</i> ‘room, cell’), for example Kilbride in Lanarkshire."]}]},{"name":"Anna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[{"name":"Anne","meanings":["A name corrpted from Hannah, q.v. It is also found several times in a male name. From Ann, Anne, we have as nicknames Nan and Nancy"]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Anna de Kirkbride was born about 1185, in Kirkbride, Cumbria, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 5 sons with Adam de Wigton II."},"et":{"about 1185–":"umbes 1185–Surnud","1185–1225":"1185–1225","1205–1266":"1205–1266","1210–1250":"1210–1250","1215–1262":"1215–1262","1220–1262":"1220–1262","1220–1267":"1220–1267","11